body: Option 3 makes sense only if you're forking the onnxruntime repo and hence using your own build. This is because the contrib ops get compiled as part of the binary. If you don't intend to do so, we strongly recommend option 1. Let me know and I can advise further.

Thank you, I was building on my own forking the repo actually.

1. So, shouldn't I build if I use Option 1?
2. May I ask any existing PRs which shows the addition of op to ORT using Option 1?
3. Say if I have got a submit a PR for that, can I raise in using Option 3 approach?
We recommend users using option 1. There are plenty of examples [here](https://github.com/microsoft/ort-customops) and in test_inference.cc.

Thank you. 
1) After adding up the code for my custom op similar to other examples in test_inference.cc, how do I test it? Is successful build enough to validate that operator is added to ORT?

2) Can I get an understanding for [test_inference.cc](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc) vs [custom_op_library.cc](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/test/testdata/custom_op_library/custom_op_library.cc)

CustomOpOne and CustomOpTwo are defined and implemented in custom_op_library.cc. And, I have realised that custom_op_test.onnx is also there in the same directory. How was graph created without actually adding the operator to ONNX?
